## They Work Better Together

Rather than choosing one approach, combine them.

A typical architecture journey might look like this.

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    Strategy["Enterprise Strategy"]
    Capability["Capabilities"]
    Products["Products"]
    Domains["Business Domains"]
    Context["C4 Context"]
    Containers["C4 Containers"]
    Components["C4 Components"]
    Deployment["Deployment"]

    Strategy --> Capability
    Capability --> Products
    Products --> Domains
    Domains --> Context
    Context --> Containers
    Containers --> Components
    Components --> Deployment
```

Each layer adds more detail while preserving the context established by the previous one.

This makes it easier for different audiences to engage with the architecture.

Executives don't need component diagrams.

Developers don't need capability maps.

Architects connect the two.

---

## Don't Force One Model to Solve Every Problem

Many architecture repositories become difficult to navigate because every question is answered using the same diagram style.

Capability maps become application diagrams.

Integration diagrams become deployment diagrams.

Context diagrams become enterprise strategy documents.

Eventually every diagram tries to explain everything—and ends up explaining nothing.

Good architecture is about choosing the appropriate viewpoint.

Not every stakeholder needs the same level of detail.

---

## A Modern Architecture Repository

A practical repository might include views like these.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Enterprise["Enterprise Strategy"]
    EDGY["EDGY Enterprise Models"]
    Capabilities["Capability Maps"]
    Domains["Domain Maps"]
    Applications["Application Landscape"]
    Integrations["Integration Views"]
    Context["C4 Context"]
    Containers["C4 Containers"]
    Components["C4 Components"]

    Enterprise --> EDGY
    EDGY --> Capabilities
    Capabilities --> Domains
    Domains --> Applications
    Applications --> Integrations
    Integrations --> Context
    Context --> Containers
    Containers --> Components
```

Every diagram has a purpose.

Every diagram answers a specific question.

Together they tell the complete architectural story.

---

## Final Thoughts

Architecture isn't about choosing the "best" notation.

It's about communicating decisions effectively.

EDGY helps us understand the enterprise.

C4 helps us understand software.

Mermaid helps us communicate both.

Used together, they provide a consistent journey from strategy to implementation while keeping architecture understandable for everyone—from executives to developers.

Rather than debating which approach is superior, consider how each contributes to a more complete architectural narrative.

The best architecture repositories don't standardize on a single diagram.

They standardize on answering the right questions.